==English==
'''GI'''
(noun): a [[soldier]] in the [[w:United States Army|US Army]] or, less commonly, any person in the [[w:US military|US military]]. 

GI is used in [[w:compound noun|compound noun]]s with any item given to a soldier by the Army, or any procedure used by the army, to distinguish it from civilian versions. (Soldiers counted cadence by chanting: "GI brush / And GI comb / Gee, I wish that I was home!") 

(verb) to clean aggressively.  As in "Top, get the unit to GI this AO before the old man arrives." 

===Etymology===
''G.I.'' was an abbreviation for ''Galvanized Iron'', a US Army clerks' term for items such as ''G.I. cans:'' trash cans that are galvanized.  ''G.I. cans'' was also used to refer sardonically to shells fired by the [[w:German Army|German Army]] in [[w:WWI|WWI]].

During the 1930s, usage of the abbreviation expanded to stand for ''Government Issue'' and applied to all articles issued in conformity with US military regulations or procedures. By WWII it had become a nickname for the soldiers themselves.

